            <div type="general">
               <p>Tāza is a city in northeastern Morocco between the Rif and the middle Atlas mountains.</p>
               <p>The city is composed of two formerly distinct towns built on separate terraces overlooking a mountain valley. The old town of Tāza is at an elevation of 585 m above sea level and is surrounded by fortifications; the newer town, established by the French in 1920, is on the fertile plain below.</p>
               <p>Tāza was founded in the late 7th century by the Miknasa Berber tribe. Because the town was on a major east-west route, and the valley of Taza was the main trade route down to the fertile plains of the Atlantic coast, the city was a strategic town during Roman and Islamic times.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:VJW5GUUD">Rguibi (2001)</rs> discusses phonological variation and
                  change in Moroccan Arabic on the basis of the Tāzi dialect.</p>
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:BEMVY9N6">Behnstedt/Benabbou (2002)</rs> offers a sketch of the phonological,
                  morphological, and lexical features of the dialects of the Tāza region, including that of the city itself. They
                  distinguish three dialects: one of the new town and two of the old town.</p>
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:HCBQQZZN">Behnstedt (2003)</rs> presents two texts with German
                  translation in  one of the old town dialects, which the author says is spoken only by a minority in Tāza and
                  will soon go extinct .</p>
            </div>
